<TEXT>
negotiators for the 22000member teachers 
union met again sunday with school district representatives to seek 
a solution to a weekold teacher walkout that has caused chaos in 
city classrooms 
representatives of the los angeles unified school district 
arrived around 815 pm more than two hours after united 
teacherlos angeles negotiators showed up for talks set to begin at 
6 pm said utla spokesman catherine carey 
it looks like the other side is dragging its feet and trying 
to prolong this thing ms carey said before they arrived she 
added that teachers were prepared for a second week in the walkout 
that began may 15 
well have our teachers out on the line again she said 
theyve invested too much at this point 
details of developments in recent talks have been sketchy 
because of a news blackout imposed by state mediator draz mrvichin 
the walkout last week played havoc with education in the nearly 
600000 student district many students walked out of classes and 
some joined teachers on picket lines in some cases students were 
housed in auditoriums because the district was unable to hire 
enough substitute teachers to fill classrooms 
during the 16monthlong labor dispute teachers have sought 
higher salaries and more say in how the districts 600plus schools 
are run 
teachers earn between 23440 and 43319 a year depending on 
experience and level of education the union wants a threeyear 
contract with a 26 percent raise including a 10 percent raise the 
first year 
the district the second largest in the nation has refused to 
go higher than a 215 percent raise over three years 
the strike which began may 15 is the districts first since a 
23day walkout in 1970 
</TEXT>
