lloyd ricks helped assemble cars for 16 
years until he lost his job now hes helping former coworkers 
rebuild their lives 
weve all been kicked in the teeth said ricks 34 now 
its time to get up and go 
ricks was a chief steward at chrysler corp until the company 
ended car production in kenosha last december laying off more than 
5000 workers the kenosha factory complex obtained by chrysler as 
part of its 1987 purchase of american motors corp had been used 
for automaking for 86 years 
in his new job as a career counselor ricks is part of a network 
that is leading people to new jobs and trying to create employment 
opportunities 
some former workers say they realize the new jobs will pay far 
less than they earned at chrysler but they have to do something 
because unemployment benefits begin to evaporate in the next month 
people are starting to get a little more desperate said 
rick phillips 35 an exautoworker people were relaxed at first 
because we had such a good benefits package 
in addition to regular unemployment compensation the package 
included a 20 million job bank from chrysler that paid full 
salary to 2200 senior workers for about three months workers with 
less seniority drew money from a subpay fund that provided 
2400 to each person 
its soon going to get to the point where the shoe really 
starts pinching said jack ward director of the workers 
assistance center established at the local united auto workers 
headquarters 
more than 2000 former autoworkers have sought help at the 
assistance center and about 300 have landed new jobs so far ward 
said the center is staffed by other former chrysler employees who 
have been trained to be counselors 
the center has computer access to job openings in wisconsin and 
illinois it also guides people to training programs at a technical 
school and provides a workshop where people can improve their math 
and english skills 
karen gibson 42 said that after brushing up her education she 
hopes to get a civil service job she had a chance to go to a 
chrysler plant in belvidere ill along with about 200 other 
former kenosha autoworkers but she and her husband did not want to 
leave their home 
in the meantime gibson said she is coping with tight finances 
although she says her unemployment benefits will continue until 
around july 
we dont go out anymore she said we dont go out to a 
movie bowling or even a tavern 
some people have started showing signs of alcohol or domestic 
problems said said karen geiken who helps run a listening 
post at the uaw headquarters so laid off workers can receive 
emotional support 
chrysler is assisting in local economic development 
were not out of the picture said thomas foley a chrysler 
executive assigned to the effort he noted that chrysler is still 
kenoshas largest employer with about 1200 people working at the 
companys engine plant 
workers state and local officials expressed betrayal when 
chrysler announced the december shutdown in january 1988 saying 
they believed the company had promised to continue production into 
the 1990s the state even threatened to sue but accepted a 
settlement that included the creation of foleys position for one 
year 
chrysler also donated vacant buildings for office and 
manufacturing space and diverted profits from 1988 wisconsin car 
sales into a trust fund to help laid off workers with living 
expenses the fund totals more than 23 million 
the crisis part of it is over said kenosha county executive 
john collins who noted that officials prepared to deal with the 
shutdown before it occurred this was an unusual plant closing 
normally you dont know about it a year ahead of time 
