<DOCNO> AP890521-0047 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
economist sir john hicks winner of the nobel 
memorial prize in economic science in 1972 has died his family 
announced sunday he was 85 
hicks died saturday at his home at blockley gloucestershire 
west of london no cause of death was announced 
he was for many years a lecturer at the london school of 
economics oxford and cambridge universities and at the university 
of manchester 
during his career hicks frequently criticized monetarism which 
advocates the control of money as the chief method of stabilizing 
the economy the theory which now prevails in britain argues that 
strict government control of the money supply is necessary to 
prevent high inflation 
hicks once commented what is wrong with monetarism is that it 
tries to put all the kinds of inflation into the same box 
his early work paralleled that of jm keynes who believed the 
money supply is largely unimportant in determining demand hicks 
was was a pioneer in streamlining the general economic equilibrium 
theory which explained the determination of prices and allocation 
of resources in an economy 
it was for work on the equilibrium theory that hicks was awarded 
the nobel memorial prize in economic science in 1972 sharing it 
with kenneth arrow of harvard university the prize was established 
in 1968 by the central bank of sweden as a memorial to alfred 
nobel who established the five nobel prizes 
hicks had been knighted in 1964 for his services to economics 
born in warwick on april 8 1904 hicks was educated at clifton 
college before winning a scholarship to balliol college oxford 
from which he graduated in 1925 
london school of economics was a lecturer from 1926 to 1935 
in 1935 hicks married another distinguished economist lady 
ursula hicks and they collaborated on numerous books on economic 
theory she died in 1985 
hicks was a cambridge lecturer for three years from 1935 after 
which he became professor of political economy at the university of 
manchester where he stayed until 1946 
later he became official fellow of nuffield college oxford 
then drummond professor of political economy at oxford university 
until his retirement in 1965 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

