<TEXT>
when financier michael milken addressed 
several hundred exshipyard workers few seemed to care that hed 
been indicted in the biggestever securities fraud case for them 
this man was a messianic cheerleader who pledged to help get their 
jobs and company back 
it may have been milkens highschool cheerleading experience 
that helped the junkbond dealer from beverly hills who delivered 
a rousing speech to the crowd at the local sons of italy hall 
his subject was the fore river shipyard which he promised to 
help the workers reopen with financing arranged by his former 
employer drexel burnham lambert inc 
when the first ship rolls in here on october first i look 
forward to coming back and shaking your hands he said 
ever since general dynamics closed the 182acre yard three years 
ago workers have dreamed of reopening it as an employeeowned 
business 
the moraleboosting april 27 speech by milken principal 
defendant in a 98count securities fraud and racketeering 
indictment announced a month earlier was only the latest twist in 
their saga 
quincy a city of 85000 people south of boston has a 
centuryold tradition of shipbuilding oldtimers proudly recount 
how they turned out the aircraft carriers wasp and lexington the 
battleship massachusetts and the first nuclear powered cruiser the 
uss long beach 
its a family tradition for a lot of us said arthur durand 
62 i worked there my father worked there and my son worked 
there it takes skill and pride to pass it on from generation to 
generation and its something we dont want to lose 
the yard was founded in 1884 by dr john watson an assistant to 
alexander graham bell and was managed after world war ii by joseph 
kennedy sr father of the late president 
for the first 75 years it thrived on innovation as wood gave 
way to steel and sails to coal and oil when the navy shrank after 
1945 the yard began a long decline slipping from a wartime peak 
of 16000 employees to 5000 in 1985 and 1000 when it closed in 
may 1986 
the next year st louisbased general dynamics sold the yard 
and several buildings for 495 million to the massachusetts water 
resources authority a quasipublic agency responsible for cleaning 
polluted boston harbor 
with support from gov michael s dukakis the mwra began 
negotiating a lease with the workers who formed massachusetts 
shipbuilders inc 
but the workers were frustrated for two years as negotiations 
foundered on such issues as hazardous waste liability and the 
mwras desire to use some of the yard for its own purposes 
the lease finally negotiated last october will allow the 
workers to use 70 acres rentfree for two years after that the 
rent will gradually rise from 100000 in the third year to 1 
million in the seventh 
to keep the workers dream alive the state has pumped nearly 
500000 into the project although most of the former general 
dynamics employees have found new jobs nearly 1000 have signed 
cards saying they would like to return to work at fore river 
peter gwyn a former general dynamics manager who is president 
of massachusetts shipbuilders said he has talked with ship owners 
about potential contracts and is optimistic the yard could begin 
building and repairing vessels again in october 
the plan hinges however on financing from drexel known for 
its ability to raise huge amounts of money through the sale of 
highyield debt securities commonly known as junk bonds the 
securities are considered riskier for buyers than other forms of 
corporate debt 
pat flanagan a vice president in the investment banks boston 
office approached the workers about junkbond financing last 
october shortly after the lease with the mwra was signed 
with milkens help flanagan worked out a 173 million package 
consisting of 13 million in commercial loans plus a 33 million 
investment by drexel and 1 million from the massachusetts capital 
resource co a group of insurance companies 
in return for their investments drexel and the insurance group 
will receive a 33 percent stake in the shipyard the remaining 67 
percent will go to the workers through an employee stock ownership 
plan 
if the us economic development administration agrees to 
guarantee 80 percent of the commercial loans the financing could 
be in place by june 30 and the first workers rehired a few weeks 
later 
drexel executives say that despite milkens appearance at the 
sons of italy hall he has been no more than a cheerleader on the 
sidelines since march when drexel agreed to dismiss him as part of 
its own deal to settle securitiesfraud charges with the government 
prior to the settlement michael was very involved both as a 
supporter of the shipyard and as somebody who was intimately 
involved in arranging the financing and helping to structure the 
transaction flanagan said 
but flanagan added his role going forward is just as a 
supporter he has no official role either as adviser or financier 
to the shipyard 
nevertheless some workers still have warm feelings toward the 
man considered responsible for helping start a flood of corporate 
takeovers that reshaped corporate america in the 1980s 
once the yard is going again said durand id be glad to 
shake his hand 
</TEXT>
